<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,152,1372]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,307,1271,1297]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Ecology:</emphasis>
it is registered at localities of 
<quantity box="[658,761,1272,1298]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.45" metricValueMax="18.0" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="m" value="94.5" valueMax="180.0" valueMin="9.0">9–180 m</quantity>
depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Lincoln, R. J." box="[847,1024,1272,1298]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref21508" refString="Lincoln, R. J. (1979) British Marine Amphipoda: Gammaridea. British Museum (Natural History), London." type="book" year="1979">Lincoln (1979)</bibRefCitation>
mentions it only down to 
<quantity box="[1330,1392,1272,1298]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="m" value="50.0">50 m</quantity>
), in cold water. 
<bibRefCitation author="Stephensen, K." box="[287,504,1309,1335]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref22022" refString="Stephensen, K. (1928) Storkrebs. II. Ringkrebs. 1. Tanglopper (Amfipoder), Danmarks Fauna. G. E. Gads Forlag, Kobenhavn, 32: 1 - XXX." type="book" year="1928">Stephensen (1928)</bibRefCitation>
mentions it being found on fine sand.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,152,1372]" box="[198,1030,1346,1372]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1883" box="[322,417,1347,1372]" class="Malacostraca" family="Stenothoidae" genus="Metopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[322,417,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the the northern distribution of the species.
</paragraph>
